Store the API key as an environment variable: You need to ensure that your GROQ_API_KEY is set as an environment variable in your operating system. You can do this by:

For Windows (Command Prompt):

bash
Copier le code
set GROQ_API_KEY=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
For Windows (PowerShell):

(last time"15/09/2024)=====>powershell
Copier le code
$env:GROQ_API_KEY="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"
For Mac/Linux: Add the following line to your ~/.bashrc, ~/.zshrc, or appropriate shell configuration file:

bash
Copier le code
export GROQ_API_KEY="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"
Then, run source ~/.bashrc or source ~/.zshrc to apply the changes.

Update your Python code: In your report_generator.py, update the way you fetch the API key:

python
Copier le code
GROQ_API_KEY = os.environ.get("GROQ_API_KEY")
This will allow your code to correctly fetch the API key from the environment variable.

Verify that the environment variable is set: You can check if the environment variable is correctly set by printing it in Python:

python
Copier le code
import os
print(os.environ.get("GROQ_API_KEY"))
If the value is None, it means the environment variable is not set correctly.

Ensure you have the groq library installed: Double-check that you have installed the groq package in your Python environment:

bash
Copier le code
pip install groq
After completing these steps, the Groq client should be able to access the correct API key and work without the error.